    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-real-life-situation">
        <title>Real Life Situation.</title>
        <p>
            
        </p>

       <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The length of a rectangle is <m>3</m> meters more than its width. Form a quadratric expression using the following information.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                First we have to identify the the values of the width and length, which are;
                <m>\text{Length} =(x + 3)</m> and <m>\text{width} = x</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                The formula of finding the area of rectangle is;
                <me>
                    Area = Length \times Width
                </me>                
            </p>
                <p>
                    Now lets form a quadratic expression using the values of lenght as;
                    <me>
                        lenght =(x + 3) \text{and} \, width = x
                    </me>
                    Substituting the values:
                    <me>
                        Area = (x + 3) \times x
                    </me>
                    Expanding the expression:
                    <me>
                        Area = x^2 + 3x
                    </me>
                    The quadratic expression ofthe area is:
                    <me>
                         x^2 + 3x    
                    </me>                    
                </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A farmer wants to create a rectangular garden with a fixed perimeter of 50 meters. 
                The length of the garden is 10 meters more than the width. 
                Form a quadratic expression to represent the area of the garden.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Let the width of the garden  be <m>W \, meters</m>, so the length of the garden is:
            <md>
                <mrow>Lenght (L) \amp = (W + 10 \, meters) </mrow>
            </md>
                The perimeter of the garden can be founde by using this formula:
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Area} \amp = L \times W </mrow>
                </md>
                Subsitituting the dimensions of the rectangle garden to the formula above:
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp = W(W \times 10) </mrow>
                </md>
                Simplifying the equation above:
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp = (W^2 + 10W) \, m^2 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The base of triangle is <m>(x + 2)</m> and height is <m>(x - 1).</m>
                Form a quadratic eaquation of the Area.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The area of a triangle is given by the formula:
                <me>
                    Area = \frac{1}{2} \times Base \times Height
                </me>
                We already have the base and the heights, using the the formula we replace the values;
                <me>
                    Area = \frac{1}{2} \times (x + 2) \times (x - 1)
                </me>
                Expanding the expression by multiplying the dimensions and grouping like terms together we have:
                <me>
                    Area = \frac{1}{2} \times (x^2 - x + 2x -2)
                </me>
                <me>
                    Area = \frac{1}{2} \times (x^2 + x - 2)
                </me>
                <me>
                    Area = \frac{1}{2}x^2 + \frac{1}{2}x - 1
                </me>
                The quaadratic expression for the area is;
                <me>
                    \frac{1}{2}x^2 + \frac{1}{2}x - 1
                </me>                
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

